r removing the javax.xml.bind dependency? It seems HSQLDB tests ran fine with this dependency, but if the native image includes it, could that be an issue? Checking generated agent configs might not be necessary, but I should ensure that user-code-filter patterns accommodate nested class names with a dollar sign.\n[thinking] \n[assistant-event] thinking_end\n[tool-call] start id=unknown\n[tool-call] delta {\"command\":\"git diff -- tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/user-code-filter.json tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/build.gradle tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/src/test/java/org_hsqldb/hsqldb/JDBCSQLXMLTest.java | sed -n '1,240p'\"}\n[tool-call] end id=call_QdF7HbPSIUGQ0vF4fh1Xa0gr|fc_05680276128df6c50169f9825b6494819dbb278a3571d19407 name=bash args={\"command\": \"git diff -- tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/user-code-filter.json tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/build.gradle tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/src/test/java/org_hsqldb/hsqldb/JDBCSQLXMLTest.java | sed -n '1,240p'\"}\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering test package dynamics**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether adding a test package to the user code filter could lead to unintended access through dynamic reflection. It seems this would only include targets without directly utilizing user tests. Maybe testing frameworks like JUnit might complicate things as they don’t typically use reflection, except through lambdas. I wonder if the Graal agent should exclude test code altogether. The concern arises about the generation of metadata for nested classes with a dollar sign, which is generally discouraged in test files.\\n\\n**Analyzing dynamic coverage configuration**\\n\\nI'm considering how dynamic coverage may now account for metadata tied to nested classes. There's a question about whether generating native image configuration for these nested test classes, which use a dollar sign, is acceptable. Alt